1 Section 1. Chapter 704 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto the
2 provisions set forth as sections 1.3 and 1.7 of this act.
3 Sec. 1.3. 1. The Commission shall open one or more investigatory dockets
4 to:
5 (a) Examine how costs for purchased fuel and purchased power are
6 currently passed through to customers.
7 (b) Examine the use of carrying charges on deferred energy accounting and
8 balances.
9 (c) Identify opportunities to mitigate the impact on customer rates which are
10 associated with fluctuations in the market for purchased fuel and purchased
11 power or other unpredictable events which affect customer rates.
12 (d) Consider elements of a potential cost-sharing adjustment mechanism for
13 purchased fuel and purchased power which is designed to align the financial
14 incentives of an electric utility with the interest of the customers of the electric
15 utility, including, without limitation:
16 (1) A cost-sharing percentage that is high enough to incentivize the
17 electric utility to keep the costs of purchased fuel and purchased power low, but
18 not low enough that the electric utility is exposed to unreasonable levels of risk
19 and volatility.
20 (2) Whether a cost-sharing adjustment mechanism is symmetrical or
21 asymmetrical.
22 (3) Whether to use a straight-sharing method or a sharing-band method.
23 (4) Whether to use a forecasted estimate of costs or historic information
24 concerning costs.
25 (5) Options to improve the transparency of any forecasted estimate of
26 costs, including the use of a forward price index and providing access to
27 forecasted estimates to interveners in proceedings of the Commission who sign
28 nondisclosure agreements.
29 (6) Implications of the inclusion of costs for purchased fuel and
30 purchased power on the participation of an electric utility in real time and day-
31 ahead markets.
32 (e) Examine existing practices [for integrated resource planning] and
33 evaluate options that reduce load and mitigate volatility in the cost of natural gas,
34 including, without limitation, demand-side management programs which are cost
35 effective, demand response and load shifting.
36 2. Before the submission of the report required by subsection 3, the
37 Commission shall submit periodic reports on the progress of each investigatory
38 docket opened pursuant to subsection 1 to the Director of the Legislative Counsel
39 Bureau for transmittal to the Joint Interim Standing Committee on Growth and
40 Infrastructure.
41 3. On or before July 1, 2026, the Commission shall submit a report on the
42 outcomes of each investigatory docket opened pursuant to subsection 1,
43 including, without limitation, the status of any regulations adopted or considered
44 as a result of the investigatory docket, to the Director of the Legislative Counsel
45 Bureau for transmittal to the Legislative Commission.
46 4. If the Commission finds it is in the public interest, as a result of the
47 investigatory docket opened pursuant to subsection 1, the Commission may adopt
48 regulations to establish a cost-sharing adjustment mechanism.
49 5. As used in this section:

